ipping examination of the politics of injury and rescue in the militarized region surrounding the US-Mexico border. Operating in this area, firefighters and paramedics are torn between their mandate as frontline state actors and their responsibility as professional rescuers, between the limits of law and pull of ethics. From this vantage they witness what unfolds when territorial sovereignty, tactical infrastructure, and the natural environment collide. Jusionyte reveals the binational brotherhood that forms in this crucible to stand in the way of catastrophe. Through beautiful ethnography and a uniquely personal perspective, Threshold provides a new way to understand politicized issues ranging from border security and undocumented migration to public access to healthcare today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEmergency medical serviceszMexican-American Border Region. 0aEmergency medical services. 0aRescue workzMexican-American Border Region. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aborder.  adivisive national debates.  aemergency responder.  aethics.  afirefighters.  afrontline.  aharsh terrain.  ahospitals.  amexico.  amigrants.  amilitarized region.  anational boundaries.  aparamedica.  apersonal perspective.  apolitics.  apreventing disasters.  aprofessional rescuers.  asaving lives.  asister towns.  atactical infrastructure.  aterritorial sovereignty.  aunited states.  aus mexico border.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052029718040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096964340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520969643423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520969643/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California P